[1
From: "George A. Robertson" <grobertson@erols.com>
Date: Thu, 22 Jul 1999 20:04:27 -0400
Source: Reuters 21 Jul 1999 [edited

Peak Passed In Deadly Fever Outbreak
-----------------------------------------
An outbreak of a rare and deadly infectious virus that killed six people in
southern Russia and raised a national media-fuelled alarm appears to be
subsiding, local emergency officials said on Tuesday.
Gennady Vyakhirev, head of the civil defense unit at the Rostov office of
the Emergencies Ministry, said 90 patients were still being treated but were
thought to be out of danger.
"We can say the peak seems to have already been reached. It is under
control," he told Reuters by telephone.
The disease first struck the village of Oblivskaya in the Rostov region,
about 1000 km (620 miles) from Moscow, earlier this month. Vyakhirev said
health officials had diagnosed it as Congo-Crimean Hemorrhagic Fever [CCHF.
[They are using the right name again! - Mod.JW
Dr Stephen Wright, a consultant at London's Hospital for Tropical Diseases,
said by telephone that the virus was transmitted mainly by bites from ticks,
although it was possible to catch it from close contact with infected
people.
It has appeared previously in Russia, the Middle East and Africa, causing
death in between 2 and 50 percent of those infected. In its worst form it
causes the patient to bleed to death through the nose, eyes, uterus or other
mucous membranes. The lurid symptoms caused a fever of speculation about
the "mystery disease" in the Russian press.
The disease has an incubation period of about 3 to 12 days, which means
doctors can determine fairly reliably when an outbreak has subsided if no
new cases appear among family members of those infected, Wright said.
